textUsed: Core Concepts. The basic ideas you need to understand before diving into machine learning algorithms and techniques.. basics, fundamentals, introduction

Machine Learning. Instead of telling a computer exactly what to do step by step, you show it many examples and let it figure out the patterns itself. Like teaching a child to recognize cats by showing

Traditional Programming vs ML. Traditional: You write the recipe (rules) yourself. ML: You show the computer many finished dishes (examples) and it figures out the recipe.. comparison, programming, pa

Statistical Learning Theory. It's the math that proves ML actually works. It answers: "If I learn from 1000 examples, why should I expect it to work on example 1001?" It gives guarantees about how muc

No Free Lunch Theorem. There's no "best" algorithm that wins at everything. An algorithm that's amazing for images might be terrible for text. You always have to pick the right tool for the job.. theo
Types of Learning. Different ways a model can learn: with answers (supervised), without answers (unsupervised), or through trial and error (reinforcement). Each approach is suited for different types

Supervised Learning. Learning with an answer key. You show the computer examples where you know the right answer, and it learns to predict answers for new examples.. supervised, labeled-data, classifi

Unsupervised Learning. Learning without an answer key. You give the computer a pile of data and say "find interesting patterns" without telling it what to look for.. unsupervised, clustering, dimensio

Semi-Supervised Learning. You have a few examples with answers and many without. The model uses the patterns in all the data to learn better than it could from just the labeled examples.. semi-supervi
Self-Supervised Learning. The data creates its own labels. Like covering part of a sentence and asking the model to guess the hidden wordthe "answer" comes from the sentence itself.. self-supervised,

Transfer Learning. Don't start from zero. Take a model that already learned something useful (like recognizing shapes from millions of images) and adapt it to your specific problem (like identifying y
Data Types. Different kinds of data need different handling. Spreadsheet data, images, text, and time-based data each have their own rules and best practices.. data, data-types, preprocessing

Structured Data. Data in neat tables with rows and columns. Like an Excel spreadsheet where every column has a name and every row is one record. Easy to search and analyze.. structured, tabular, datab
Unstructured Data. Data that doesn't fit in a spreadsheet. Raw text, photos, videos, audio recordingsthings you can't easily put in rows and columns.. unstructured, text, images, audio, nlp, computer

Data Quality & Preprocessing. Making sure your data is clean and ready to use. Fixing errors, filling in blanks, and removing weird values so the model can learn properly.. data-quality, preprocessing

Missing Values. Empty cells in your data. Sometimes data wasn't collected, was corrupted, or the person skipped a question. You need to decide: delete the row, fill in a guess, or use an algorithm tha
Imputation. Filling in the blanks with educated guesses. Simple: use the average. Smart: use other information to predict what the missing value probably was.. imputation, missing-data, preprocessing

Outliers. Weird data points that don't fit the pattern. Could be mistakes (typo: age 500 instead of 50) or real rare cases (billionaire in income survey). Need to decide if they're errors to fix or va

Feature Engineering. Creating better inputs for your model. Raw data might not be in the most useful form. You transform it, combine it, or create new information that helps the model learn patterns..

Feature Scaling. Making features comparable. If one feature is 0-1 and another is 0-1,000,000, the big one dominates unfairly. Scaling puts them on similar footing.. scaling, normalization, standardiz
Normalization (Min-Max). Squish all values between 0 and 1. The smallest becomes 0, largest becomes 1, everything else proportionally in between.. normalization, min-max, scaling, preprocessing

Standardization (Z-Score). Transform so average is 0 and spread is 1. Values tell you "how many standard deviations from average." A value of +2 means "2 standard deviations above average.". standardi

One-Hot Encoding. Make a new column for each category. If there are 3 colors, make 3 columns. Each row has exactly one "1" showing which category it belongs to.. encoding, categorical, one-hot, prepro

Train/Validation/Test Split. Divide your data into three piles: one to learn from (training), one to tune settings (validation), and one final exam (test). Never peek at the test set until you're done

Cross-Validation. Don't rely on one random split. Split your data multiple ways, train and test on each split, average the results. Gives a more reliable estimate than one lucky or unlucky split.. cro

Hypothesis Space. All the possible patterns your model CAN learn. A straight line can only represent lines. A neural network can represent almost anything. Your model can only learn functions within i

Loss Functions. A number that says "how wrong is the model?" Lower is better. The model adjusts weights to make this number smaller. Different loss functions penalize errors differently.. loss-functio
Mean Squared Error (MSE). Average of (prediction - actual). Big errors get penalized way more than small errors because of the squaring. A $100 error becomes 10,000; a $10 error becomes 100.. mse, lo

Cross-Entropy Loss. Measures how surprised the model is by the correct answer. If model says "99% dog" and it's actually a cat, loss is huge. If model says "51% cat" and it's a cat, loss is small.. cr
Bias-Variance Tradeoff. Too simple = consistent but wrong (high bias). Too complex = right on training data but wrong on new data (high variance). You want the Goldilocks zonejust complex enough.. bi

Bias. The error from making wrong assumptions. A simple model might assume everything is a straight line, but real data is curved. No matter how much data you give it, it'll keep getting the curve wro
Variance. The error from being too sensitive. A complex model that fits training data perfectly might be just fitting noise. Train on slightly different data and you get a totally different model. It
Underfitting. Model is too simple. It can't even do well on training data, let alone new data. Like trying to fit a curved road with a straight rulerjust doesn't work.. underfitting, bias, model-comp
Overfitting. Model memorized the training data instead of learning patterns. It knows every quirk of training examples but fails on new ones. Like memorizing test answers instead of understanding the

Generalization. How well the model works on new data it's never seen. Training accuracy doesn't matter if the model fails on fresh data. Generalization is the whole point of ML.. generalization, test-
Gradient-Based Optimization. Find which way is downhill (gradient), take a step that way. Repeat until you reach the bottom (minimum loss). The foundation of how neural networks learn.. optimization,

Gradient. Arrow pointing uphill. For each weight, gradient says "if you increase this weight, loss goes up/down by this much." Go the opposite direction (downhill) to reduce loss.. gradient, calculus,
Gradient Descent. Walk downhill. Calculate which direction is steepest down, take a step that way. Repeat until you reach the bottom (minimum loss).. gradient-descent, optimization, training

Learning Rate. How big a step to take downhill. Too big: you jump past the bottom and bounce around. Too small: takes forever to get there. Just right: smooth descent to minimum.. learning-rate, hyper
Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD). Instead of computing the perfect gradient from ALL data (slow), estimate it from one random example (fast, noisy). Like polling 100 people instead of entire country
Momentum. Remember which direction you've been going. Instead of just following current gradient, combine it with previous direction. Like a ball rollingit builds speed going the same direction and s

Adam Optimizer. The best of both worlds: momentum (remember direction) + adaptive learning rate (different speed for each weight). Parameters that have been getting consistent gradients move faster; i
Regularization Techniques. Rules to keep the model from getting too complicated. Without constraints, models memorize training data. Regularization says "keep it simple"which usually means it'll work
L2 Regularization (Ridge). Penalty for big weights. The bigger your weights, the more you're penalized. Keeps all weights small rather than having a few huge ones. Like a taxyou can have big weights,

L1 Regularization (Lasso). Penalty that creates zeros. Some weights get driven all the way to zero (feature eliminated). L2 makes weights small; L1 makes some weights disappear entirely. Good for sele
Dropout. Randomly turn off some neurons during training. Forces the network to not rely on any single neuron too muchlike making sure multiple students understand the material, not just one. At test
Early Stopping. Stop training before the model starts memorizing. Watch validation accuracywhen it stops improving (or gets worse), stop training even if training accuracy is still going up. Training

Batch Normalization. After each layer, normalize the outputs: make mean=0, variance=1 across the batch. Then let the model learn the best mean and variance. Keeps values in a nice range throughout tra
Classification Metrics. Different ways to measure if your classifier is doing a good job. Overall accuracy isn't always enoughsometimes you care more about catching all the positives (recall) or bein

Confusion Matrix. A table showing what the model predicted vs what was actually true. Shows exactly where the model is right and where it's wrong. Four boxes: correct positives, correct negatives, wro

Accuracy. Percentage of predictions that are correct. Simple but can be deceiving. If 99% of emails are not spam, predicting "not spam" always gives 99% accuracy but catches zero spam.. accuracy, clas

Precision. Of all the times the model said "positive," how often was it right? High precision = few false alarms. When model says "yes," you can trust it.. precision, classification, metrics, false-po

Recall (Sensitivity). Of all the actual positives, how many did the model find? High recall = few misses. Model catches most of the positives that exist.. recall, sensitivity, classification, metrics,
F1 Score. Combined score balancing precision and recall. You can't game it by being extreme on one metricboth need to be good. If precision is 100% but recall is 10%, F1 is only 18%.. f1-score, class
AUC-ROC. How good is the model at ranking positives above negatives, regardless of threshold? AUC=0.5 means random, AUC=1.0 means perfect separation. Useful because it's threshold-independentevaluate

Clustering. Find natural groups in data without being told what groups exist. Customers might naturally cluster into "budget shoppers," "luxury buyers," etc. The algorithm discovers these groups from

K-Means Clustering. Pick K cluster centers, assign each point to the nearest center, move centers to the middle of their points, repeat. Simple and fast. Works best when clusters are ball-shaped and s
Elbow Method. Try different numbers of clusters, plot the "tightness" of clusters. Initially, adding clusters helps a lot. At some point, adding more doesn't help muchthat's the elbow. Choose K at th

Hierarchical Clustering. Build a tree of clusters from bottom up. Start with each point alone. Merge the two closest clusters. Repeat until one cluster remains. Cut the tree at any level to get differ

DBSCAN. Find dense regions separated by sparse regions. A point is "core" if it has enough neighbors nearby. Clusters are connected dense regions. Points in sparse areas are labeled as noise. Great fo

Gaussian Mixture Model. Assume data comes from K bell curves (Gaussians) overlapping. Find the best K bell curves to explain the data. Unlike K-means, gives probabilities (soft assignments) and handle
Dimensionality Reduction. Reduce the number of features while keeping important information. 1000 features  50 features. Helps visualization, speeds up training, and removes noise. Different methods

Principal Component Analysis (PCA). Find the directions where data varies most. Project data onto these directions. First direction (PC1) is most important, then PC2, etc. Like finding the "main axes"

t-SNE. Arrange points in 2D so nearby points stay nearby, far points stay far. Optimizes a "similarity" match between original and reduced space. Amazing for visualization, reveals clusters and patter

UMAP. Like t-SNE but faster, preserves more global structure, and can apply to new data. The current state-of-the-art for visualization. Good for both visualization and actual dimensionality reduction
Autoencoders for Dimensionality Reduction. Train a neural network to compress and decompress data. The compression in the middle is your reduced representation. Learns whatever compression works best

Density Estimation. Learn the shape of your data distribution. Where is data concentrated? Where is it sparse? Useful for understanding data, detecting outliers, and generating new samples.. unsupervi

Kernel Density Estimation (KDE). Put a small bump (Gaussian) at each data point, add them all up. More data points nearby = higher density. Bandwidth controls smoothness: small = bumpy, large = smooth

Anomaly Detection. Find the weird ones. Anomalies are data points that don't fit the normal pattern. Could be fraud, equipment failure, or data errors. Different methods define "unusual" differently..
Isolation Forest. Try to isolate each point with random splits. Normal points are buried in clustersneed many splits. Anomalies are differentcan be isolated quickly. Points that isolate easily are a
One-Class SVM. Draw a boundary around normal data. Everything outside the boundary is an anomaly. Uses SVM techniques to find the best boundary. Train on normal examples onlyno need for labeled anoma
Autoencoder Anomaly Detection. Train autoencoder on normal data. It learns to reconstruct normal patterns well. Anomalies look different  can't reconstruct them well  high error = anomaly.. unsuperv

Autoencoder. Compress data, then decompress it back. The compressed form in the middle captures the essence. Like learning to describe images with few words, then recreating images from those descript

Variational Autoencoder (VAE). Autoencoder where the compressed form is a probability distribution, not a fixed point. Adds randomness during training. Result: can sample from the latent space to gene
Denoising Autoencoder. Add noise to input, try to reconstruct the clean version. Can't just memorizemust truly understand the data to remove noise. Learns more meaningful representations than regular

Generative Adversarial Network. Two networks compete: one creates fakes, one detects fakes. Generator gets better at making fakes; Discriminator gets better at detecting them. Eventually, Generator cr

Generator Network. Creates fake data from random numbers. Starts with random noise, applies neural network transformations to produce images, audio, or text. Learns to produce outputs that fool the Di

Discriminator Network. A detective trying to spot fakes. Looks at samples and outputs probability of being real. Trained on both real data and Generator's fakes. Provides feedback to Generator about w
Mode Collapse. Generator takes shortcutsproduces only a few types of samples that fool Discriminator. Like a counterfeiter who only makes $20 bills perfectly but can't make other denominations. Varie
Wasserstein GAN (WGAN). A more stable GAN using a different way to measure how different fake and real distributions are. The Critic gives scores instead of probabilities. Training is smootherloss ac
StyleGAN. Advanced GAN for high-quality face generation. Separates "style" (attributes like hair color, age) from "structure." Can mix styles from different latentstake face shape from one, hair from

Normalizing Flow. Transform simple distribution to complex one through a chain of reversible steps. Can compute exact probability of any data point. Can generate new samples by sampling from simple di

Diffusion Model. Slowly destroy data by adding noise, then learn to reverse the destruction. To generate: start with pure noise, gradually remove it to reveal a realistic sample. Like watching film gr

DDPM (Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Model). The foundational paper that made diffusion models work well. Defined exact math for noising/denoising. Uses a U-Net to predict noise at each step. Simpl
Stable Diffusion. Diffusion in a compressed space instead of pixel spacemuch faster! Use a text description to guide what image is generated. Open source and runs on regular GPUs. Powers many image g
Language Model. Predict the next word given previous words. "The cat sat on the ___"  "mat" (high probability). Trained on massive text, learns grammar, facts, and reasoning patterns. Foundation of C

Perplexity. How surprised is the model by the text? Lower perplexity = less surprised = better predictions. If perplexity is 100, it's like the model is confused between 100 equally likely words. Good

Large Language Model (LLM). Very large neural networks trained on internet-scale text. At sufficient size, they learn to follow instructions, reason about problems, and perform tasks they weren't expl
In-Context Learning. Give the model examples in the prompt, and it figures out the pattern. No training neededjust show it what you want. "Q: 2+2? A: 4. Q: 3+5? A: 8. Q: 7+3? A:"  Model outputs "10"

RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback). Train the model to match human preferences. Humans rank different outputs. Train a "reward model" to predict rankings. Use RL to make the language mo

Prompt Engineering. Craft the right question to get the right answer. Small changes in phrasing dramatically affect outputs. Adding "Let's think step by step" improves reasoning. Examples in the promp
Fine-Tuning LLMs. Adapt the general LLM to your specific needs. Full fine-tuning: expensive but thorough. LoRA: add small trainable adapterscheap and effective. Like teaching a generalist to speciali

Ensemble Learning. Combine many models to make a better one. Like asking 100 experts instead of just onethey'll make different mistakes, but the majority is usually right. The "wisdom of crowds" for

Wisdom of Crowds. Many guesses averaged together beat one expert guess. If 100 people guess how many jellybeans are in a jar, the average is usually very close to the truth, even though individuals ar
Base Learner. The individual models that get combined. They don't have to be great on their ownjust slightly better than guessing. Decision trees are popular base learners because they're fast and di

Model Diversity. Ensemble members should disagree on different examples. If all models make the same mistakes, combining them doesn't help. Create diversity through different data, different features,

Bagging. Create different training sets by randomly sampling with replacement. Train a model on each sample, then average their predictions. Each model sees a slightly different version of the data, c
Bootstrap Sampling. Pick random examples, allowing repeats. With N examples, draw N timessome examples appear multiple times, some don't appear at all. This randomness creates different training sets
Out-of-Bag Error. Each example is "out of bag" for some models (wasn't in their training sample). Use those models to predict for that exampleit's like a test set they never saw. Do this for all exam

Random Forest. Bagging + random feature selection. Each tree sees different data AND can only use a random subset of features at each split. Double randomness = more diversity = better ensemble. Often

Random Subspace Method. Each model only sees some features. Instead of hiding examples, hide columns. Model 1 might see [age, income], Model 2 sees [education, zipcode]. Each model specializes in diff
Extra Trees. Random Forest picks the best split from random features. Extra Trees picks a random split point tooeven more randomness. Faster training, more diverse trees, surprisingly effective. Trad

Boosting. Train models one at a time, each fixing the previous one's mistakes. First model does its best. Second model focuses on what the first got wrong. Third model focuses on remaining errors. Kee

AdaBoost. Give each example a weight. Misclassified examples get heavier (more important). Next model pays more attention to heavy examples. After many rounds, hard examples have been repeatedly targe

Gradient Boosting. Each new model predicts the remaining error. Model 1 predicts the target. Model 2 predicts what Model 1 got wrong (the residual). Model 3 predicts what's still wrong. Add all predic

XGBoost. Gradient boosting on steroids. Faster, handles missing data, prevents overfitting with regularization, works at scale. The go-to algorithm for structured data. Won countless Kaggle competitio

LightGBM. Even faster gradient boosting for big data. Groups feature values into bins (histograms) instead of checking every value. Grows trees leaf-by-leaf (picking best leaf to split) rather than le
CatBoost. Gradient boosting that handles categories natively. No need to one-hot encode or manually encode categorical featuresCatBoost does it smartly while avoiding data leakage. Great when you hav
Learning Rate in Boosting. How much each new tree contributes. Learning rate 1.0 = full contribution. Learning rate 0.1 = only 10% contribution. Smaller rates are more conservativeneed more trees but

Stacking. Train a model to combine other models. Instead of averaging, learn the best way to combine. Maybe Random Forest is good for some examples, while SVM is better for others. The meta-learner fi

Blending. Like stacking but simpler. Hold out some training data. Train base models on the rest. Make predictions on the holdout. Train a combiner on those predictions. Faster than full cross-validati

Voting Ensemble. Democracy for models. Hard voting: each model votes for a class, majority wins. Soft voting: average the probability predictions. Simple, no training needed, often surprisingly effect

Weighted Averaging. Better models get more say. If Random Forest has 90% accuracy and SVM has 70%, Random Forest should count more. Assign weights proportional to performance or optimize them.. ensemb

Artificial Neuron. A tiny decision-maker. Takes several inputs, multiplies each by a weight (importance), adds them up, then decides whether to "fire" based on the total. Many neurons working together

Perceptron. The original neural network: one neuron with a yes/no output. Can only draw a straight line to separate classes. Works great for simple problems, fails completely on complex ones like XOR.

Multilayer Perceptron (MLP). Stack multiple layers of neurons together. Input layer receives data, hidden layers learn patterns, output layer makes predictions. Adding hidden layers allows learning co
Feedforward Network. Information flows forward only, never backward or in loops. Input goes in, passes through layers, output comes out. No memory of previous inputs. Simple, efficient, and the basis
Dense Layer (Fully Connected). Every input connects to every output. If the previous layer has 100 neurons and this layer has 50, there are 10050 = 5000 connections. Flexible but expensive. Used when

Activation Function. The "decision-maker" inside each neuron. Without activation functions, a 100-layer network would behave like a single layer. Activations add the nonlinearity that allows deep lear

ReLU (Rectified Linear Unit). If positive, output as-is. If negative, output zero. Super simple, super fast. Works great in practice. The default choice for most neural networks.. neural-networks, dee

Leaky ReLU. ReLU but with a small slope for negative values instead of flat zero. Negative inputs still produce a small output (and gradient), preventing dead neurons.. neural-networks, deep-learning,

Tanh. Squashes values to range -1 to 1. Zero-centered (unlike sigmoid's 0 to 1). Often used in recurrent networks. Gradient vanishes for very large or small inputs.. neural-networks, deep-learning, ta

GELU. A smooth version of ReLU that weights inputs by how positive they are (probabilistically). The activation used in transformers like BERT and GPT. Smoother than ReLU, often works better for langu

Swish. The input multiplied by its own sigmoid. Self-gated: large positive inputs pass through, negative inputs are suppressed but not hard zeroed. Smooth, works well in deep networks.. neural-network

Backpropagation. How neural networks learn. After making a prediction, figure out how much each weight contributed to the error. Start from the output, work backward through each layer, adjusting weig

Computational Graph. A flowchart of math operations. Draw how inputs become outputs through operations. Forward: follow arrows to compute result. Backward: follow arrows in reverse to compute gradient

Vanishing Gradient. Gradients shrink as they travel backward through layers. By the time they reach early layers, they're so small the network can't learn. Deep networks used to be impossible to train

Exploding Gradient. Gradients grow so large they break training. Weights update by huge amounts, oscillating wildly or overflowing to infinity. Common in recurrent networks. Fixed by clipping gradient

Weight Initialization. How to set initial weights before training. Too small: signal dies out. Too large: activations saturate or explode. Just right: signal flows through all layers. The starting poi

Xavier Initialization. Initialize weights based on how many neurons connect in and out. Smaller weights for layers with many connections. Keeps signal strength consistent as it flows through the netwo
He Initialization. Like Xavier but adjusted for ReLU. Since ReLU zeros out half the values, He init uses larger weights (2 factor) to compensate. The go-to for ReLU networks.. neural-networks, deep-l

Convolutional Neural Network. Neural networks designed for images. Instead of connecting every pixel to every neuron (expensive!), use small filters that slide across the image detecting patterns. Fir
Convolution Operation. A small filter slides across the image, multiplying and summing at each position. Different filters detect different patterns: one might find vertical edges, another horizontal
Pooling Layer. Shrink the image by summarizing small regions. Max pooling: keep the largest value in each 22 block (preserves strongest features). Average pooling: keep the average (smoother). Makes

Stride and Padding. Stride: how far the filter moves each step. Bigger stride = smaller output.
Padding: add border around the image. Keeps size constant and allows filters to see edge pixels.. deep-l

Receptive Field. How much of the original image does one neuron "see"? First layer neurons see just a small patch. Deep layer neurons effectively see most of the image because they combine info from m

Feature Map. The result of one filter scanning an image. High values where the pattern is found, low values elsewhere. Like a heat map of "where is this pattern?" Many filters = many feature maps = ma
Recurrent Neural Network. A network that remembers. Processes sequences one element at a time, keeping a "memory" (hidden state) that gets updated at each step. Good for text, audio, time seriesanyth

Hidden State. The RNN's memory. A vector that summarizes everything it's seen so far. Gets updated with each new input. Can be used to predict the next word, classify the sequence, or encode it for an

LSTM (Long Short-Term Memory). RNN with a better memory. Has gates that decide: what to forget, what to remember, what to output. The special "cell state" can carry important information unchanged acr

GRU (Gated Recurrent Unit). A simpler LSTM. Two gates instead of three, no separate cell state. Reset gate: how much to ignore the past. Update gate: balance between old state and new state. Faster, l

Bidirectional RNN. Run the sequence forward AND backward. Each position knows what came before AND what comes after. For understanding "bank" in "I deposited money at the bank," seeing future words he

Attention Mechanism. Let the model focus on relevant parts. Like highlighting important words when reading. For each position, calculate how relevant every other position is, then take a weighted aver

Self-Attention. Each word looks at every other word in the same sentence to understand context. "Bank" in "river bank" attends to "river" to understand its meaning. Every position can directly connect

Multi-Head Attention. Multiple attention patterns at once. One head might focus on nearby words, another on verbs, another on pronouns. Different perspectives combined give richer understanding than s

Transformer Architecture. A powerful architecture using attention instead of recurrence. Processes all positions simultaneously (fast!), directly connects any positions (good for long-range patterns),

Positional Encoding. Tell the model where each word is. Without positions, "dog bites man" = "man bites dog" to attention. Positional encoding adds a unique pattern to each position. Model learns to u

Encoder-Decoder Architecture. Two parts: encoder reads and understands the input, decoder generates the output. Encoder sees the whole input at once. Decoder generates one token at a time, looking bac

Decoder-Only Architecture. Just the decoder part, no encoder. Predicts the next word based on all previous words. The architecture behind ChatGPT. Can handle many tasks by framing them as text generat
Sparse Attention. Don't attend to everythingpick important positions. Nearby words, global summary tokens, and some random connections. Much faster than full attention, can handle much longer documen
Linear Attention. Make attention linear instead of quadratic. Use math tricks to avoid computing all n pairs. Much faster for long sequences, with some quality trade-off.. deep-learning, architecture

State Space Model (SSM). An alternative to transformers for sequences. Based on control theory mathematics. Can process sequences as efficiently as CNNs while handling long-range dependencies like RNN

Mamba. A selective state space model where the "memory" adapts based on what it's reading. Can decide what to remember and forget based on content, like attention but with linear complexity. Much fast

Domain Adaptation. Make models work when training and deployment data look different. Trained on photos, deployed on sketches. Trained in lab conditions, deployed in the real world. Adapt the model to
Zero-Shot Learning. Recognize things you've never seen examples of. Trained on cats and dogs. Can classify "zebra" by knowing it's "horse-like with stripes." Uses descriptions or attributes to bridge
Few-Shot Learning. Learn from just a few examples. Humans can recognize a new animal from one picture. Few-shot learning teaches models this ability. Show 5 examples of a new class, and the model can
Reinforcement Learning. Learn by trial and error. Take actions, get rewards (or punishments), learn what works. Like training a dog with treats. No labeled examplesjust try things and learn from outc

Markov Decision Process (MDP). The math framework for RL. States you can be in, actions you can take, probabilities of what happens next, and rewards you get. The goal: find the best strategy (policy)
Q-Learning. Learn the value of each action in each situation. "In this state, going left gives +10 future reward, going right gives +5." Pick actions with highest Q-values. Learn from any experience,

Policy Gradient. Directly improve the policy (decision-making rules). If an action led to good outcomes, make it more likely. If it led to bad outcomes, make it less likely. Adjusts probabilities base

Actor-Critic. Two networks working together. Actor decides what to do. Critic evaluates how good the situation is. Critic's feedback helps Actor learn faster and more stably. Like having both a player

Contrastive Learning. Learn by comparison. "These two augmented versions of the same image should have similar embeddings. This other image should be different." Pushes and pulls in embedding space un
Masked Language Modeling. Hide some words, guess them from context. "The ___ chased the mouse"  "cat". Both left and right context help. After seeing millions of sentences, the model deeply understan

Sequence Labeling. Label each item in a sequence. For each word: is it a noun, verb, adjective? Is it a person name, location, or organization? Each position gets its own label.. sequence, structured,

Conditional Random Field (CRF). Model the whole label sequence, not just individual labels. "B-PER should be followed by I-PER, not I-ORG." Learns label transition patterns. Predicts the globally best
Named Entity Recognition (NER). Find names of people, places, companies, dates in text. "Apple announced new products"  Apple is B-ORG (organization). Crucial for extracting structured information fr
